BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on developments related to the elections scheduled for 
29 May 1994. 
  On 9 April several politicians expressed their support to 
Liberal Party presidential candidate Ernesto Samper, among them 
conservative leaders Jaime Arias Ramirez, Gustavo Rodriguez 
Vargas, and Alvaro Paba. Senators Bernardo Gutierrez and Anibal 
Palacios, of the Hope, Peace, and Liberty Party, and Pastor 
Dario Silva Silva also announced they will support Samper. 
(Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 1 in Spanish 
1800 9 Apr 94) 
  During his tour of the Atlantic Coast, Conservative Party 
presidential candidate Andres Pastrana visited the municipality 
of Arjona, Bolivar Department. In Santa Marta, more than 15,000 
persons gathered at the Cathedral Plaza to participate in a 
rally. A large crowd welcomed him in Soledad, Atlantico. On 9 
April, Pastrana visited several towns in Sucre and Bolivar 
Departments, including Tolu, Since, Maria la Baja, and 
Cincelejo. Pastrana was accompanied by several Liberal Party, 
PL, leaders, who explained their reasons for supporting him. 
(Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 1 in Spanish 
0130 GMT 10 Apr 94) 
  Radio station RCN on 11 April reported the results of a poll 
conducted by Infomaster Colombia, which showed that PL candidate 
Ernesto Samper would be the chosen candidate to replace 
President Cesar Gaviria, but would have to go to runoff 
elections with Conservative candidate Andres Pastrana. 
According to the survey, Samper would receive 47 percent of the 
votes in the first round of elections scheduled for 29 May, 
while Conservative Party candidate would garner 38 percent. 
Samper would win the runoff elections with 48 percent of the 
votes, while Pastrana would obtain 41 percent. The survey 
reflects the opinion of some 1,550 voters polled in 17 cities 
from 28 march to 1 April. (Hamburg DPA in Spanish 1855 GMT 11 
Apr 94) 
  Presidential candidate Ernesto Samper referred to the 
unemployment problem, saying that "we hope to create 350,000 
jobs through microenterprises, 120,000 through infrastructure, 
100,000 in social investments, and 200,000 by doubling our 
exports." (Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 1 in 
Spanish 0000 GMT 13 Apr 94) 

